{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17585794","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17585794"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T08:18:42+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T08:18:42+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15014"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15014","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15014"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.22,0.61,0.13,0.02,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7702"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66853"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7702","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7702"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15014"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52307"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4936"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"4944"},{"type":"tags","id":"5254"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18818"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18821"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66853","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/66853"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAntibiotics work through various mechanisms to inhibit bacterial growth and survival. Understanding these mechanisms is crucial for appropriate antibiotic selection.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following antibiotics inhibits bacterial RNA polymerase?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Quinolones","Rifampicin","Sulfonamides","Trimethoprim","Metronidazole"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct answer is \u003Cstrong\u003Erifampicin\u003C/strong\u003E, which specifically binds to bacterial DNA-dependent RNA polymerase, thereby blocking transcription of bacterial genes. This mechanism makes it particularly effective against actively growing bacteria.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other antibiotics work through different mechanisms:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EQuinolones\u003C/strong\u003E inhibit bacterial DNA gyrase and topoisomerase IV, preventing DNA replication\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESulfonamides\u003C/strong\u003E competitively inhibit para-aminobenzoic acid in the folate synthesis pathway\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETrimethoprim\u003C/strong\u003E blocks bacterial dihydrofolate reductase, interfering with folate metabolism\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMetronidazole\u003C/strong\u003E is reduced to active metabolites that damage bacterial DNA through direct interaction\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUnderstanding these distinct mechanisms of action is important as it helps explain their spectrum of activity, potential for resistance development, and appropriate clinical use.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Rifampicin works by binding to bacterial DNA-dependent RNA polymerase, inhibiting bacterial transcription","Different antibiotics target distinct bacterial processes including DNA synthesis, RNA synthesis, protein synthesis, and cell wall synthesis","Understanding antibiotic mechanisms of action helps predict their spectrum of activity and potential resistance mechanisms"],"references":["Hauser, A. (2018). Antibiotic basics for clinicians. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science","Mosaei H, Harbottle J. Mechanisms of antibiotics inhibiting bacterial RNA polymerase. Biochem Soc Trans. 2019 Feb 28;47(1):339-350. doi: 10.1042/BST20180499. Epub 2019 Jan 15. PMID: 30647141."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52307"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15014"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52307","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/52307"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-02T21:18:28+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-02T21:21:15+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7702"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66853"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4936","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4936"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udee1\ufe0f","name":"Immune System","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-17T23:16:52+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-27T10:23:44+10:30"},"relationship